The Cauchy integral formula may look innocent, but it contains a profound element. Namely, that it reduces the value of a holomorphic function at a point f(z) to an integral of f(w)/(w - z) on a surrounding circle. This expression as a function of z is smooth and easy to deal with, and we can leverage this to obtain properties of the original function, seemingly out of thin air. Consider for example the derivative of this function, we can compute
  \begin {aligned}     \frac {f(z) - f(z_0)}{z - z_0} &= \frac {1}{2 \pi  i (z - z_0)} \int _\gamma  f(w) \left ( \frac {1}{w - z} - \frac {1}{w - z_0} \right ) \operatorname {d}\mathclose {w} \\     &= \frac {1}{2 \pi  i} \int _\gamma  \frac {f(w)}{(w - z) (w - z_0)} \operatorname {d}\mathclose {w}.   \end {aligned}
  But this obviously converges to \int _\gamma  f(w) / (w - z_0)^2 \operatorname {d}\mathclose {w} as z \to  z_0, since the integrand converges uniformly, thanks to the nice behavior of f(w)/(w - z) as a function of z as previously mentioned. We have therefore also obtained a formula for the derivative of a holomorphic function. This can now be repeated to obtain higher derivatives.

Removing a smaller disk of radius r around a. Then \frac {f(z) - f(a)}{z - a} is an analytic function in this region. Applying Greenâ€™s formula we have
    \int _{\gamma } \frac {f(z) - f(a)}{z - a} \operatorname {d}\mathclose {z} = \int _{\gamma '} \frac {f(z) - f(a)}{z - a} \operatorname {d}\mathclose {z}
    where \gamma  is the original circle, and \gamma ' is the smaller circle. Now since f is holomorphic, the integrand has a limit as z \to  a by definition, so in particular it is bounded for small enough r. Therefore the right hand side is bounded by 2 \pi  r C for a constant C, which goes to zero. So the left hand side must be zero since it does not depend on r.

A holomorphic function defined on an open set U \subseteq  \mathbb {C} is a complex-valued function that is complex differentiable at every point. In other words, the limit
  f'(z) = \lim _{h \to  0} \frac {f(z + h) - f(z)}{h}
  exists for all z \in  U.
